        "title": {
          "english": "Replying with 'Yes'"
        },
        "text": "To say \"yes\" in Levantine Arabic, you can use either \"آه\" or \"أيوا\". Both are very common and interchangeable in most contexts.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "آه",
            "english": "Yes",
            "transliteration": "āh"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أيوا",
            "english": "Yes",
            "transliteration": "aywa"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Replying with 'No'"
        },
        "text": "To say \"no\" in Levantine Arabic, you use \"لأ\". This is a straightforward negation.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "لأ",
            "english": "No",
            "transliteration": "laʾ"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking simple Yes/No questions"
        },
        "text": "To ask a yes/no question like \"Is this a book?\" or \"Is this a table?\", you simply state the phrase with a rising intonation at the end. The words \"هادا\" (hada) for masculine and \"هادي\" (hadi) for feminine are used to mean \"this is\".",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "هادا كتاب؟",
            "english": "Is this a book?",
            "transliteration": "Hada kitāb?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هادي طاولة؟",
            "english": "Is this a table?",
            "transliteration": "Hadi ṭāwleh?"
          }
        ]
      }
